				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Investors Await Cues on Modi&#8217;s Economic Policy</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Neha Thirani Bagri			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-05-21T09:32:49+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May 21, 2014 5:32 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May 21, 2014 5:32 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/21/world/asia/21-arun-IndiaInk/21-arun-IndiaInk-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/21/world/asia/21-arun-IndiaInk/21-arun-IndiaInk-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/21/world/asia/21-arun-IndiaInk/21-arun-IndiaInk-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002892980" width="592" height="394" alt="Arun Jaitley, a senior leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party, arriving at the Parliament house in New Delhi on Tuesday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="394"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Arun Jaitley, a senior leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party, arriving at the Parliament house in New Delhi on Tuesday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Prakash Singh/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/21/investors-await-cues-on-modis-economic-policy/" data-title="Investors Await Cues on Modi&#8217;s Economic Policy" data-description="Foreign and domestic investors are keenly awaiting the appointment of the finance minister and the announcement of the new governmentâs first budget, while keeping tabs on speculation about a possible change in leadership at the central bank.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><br />
MUMBAI, IndiaÂ âÂ As the Bharatiya Janata Party and Narendra Modi, the prime minister-elect, begin to discuss the allocation of key cabinet positions, investorsâ eyes are on one key appointment â that of the countryâs finance minister, who will be responsible for steering Indiaâs foundering economy to calm waters.</p>
<div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><h6 class="kicker"><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/category/india-votes/">India Votes</a></h6><p class="summary">News and analysis on the worldâs largest election. </p></div></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Domestic and foreign investors and businesses are also waiting on the announcement of the new governmentâs first budget, while keeping tabs on speculation about a possible change in leadership at the central bank.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">People close to the party and economists say the front-runner for the post of finance minister, who will also be tasked with restoring foreign investorsâ confidence in India, appears to beÂ <a href="//www.livemint.com/Politics/tTJD6FzvdsKDOoR2I67VpK/Narendra-Modi-is-said-to-favour-Arun-Jaitley-as-next-finance.html" target="_blank">Arun Jaitley</a>, a senior B.J.P. leader. Mr. Jaitley, who lost in <a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/30/b-j-p-s-urbane-face-nervous-in-electoral-debut-in-amritsar/">his electoral debut in Amritsar</a> in the state of Punjab, previously served as the minister of commerce and industry and the minister of law and justice in the B.J.P.-led National Democratic Alliance government, which governed from 1998 to 2004.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In February, Mr. Jaitley <a href="//www.ndtv.com/article/india/finance-minister-relieved-his-successor-in-trouble-writes-arun-jaitley-484641" target="_blank">remarked</a>, rather tellingly, that the current finance minister, P. Chidambaram, would leave a troubling legacy for his successor.<br />
<span id="more-76107"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another contender whose name is making the rounds isÂ <a href="//ibnlive.in.com/news/modi-keen-on-mha-jaitley-mea-joshi-defence-shourie-finance-sources/472837-37-64.html" target="_blank">Arun Shourie</a>, a senior B.J.P. politician and former minister ofÂ disinvestment, communications and information technology in the National Democratic Alliance government. He has also worked as an economist at the World Bank.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">People with knowledge of the matter have suggestedÂ that a technocrat and party outsider likeÂ Deepak Parekh, chairman of HDFC Bank, or K.V. Kamath, chairman ofÂ ICICI Bank, could beÂ named finance minister.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf Mr. Modi chooses a pro-reform technocrat from outside the political system who knows the financial market or is from the financial market, such as Deepak Parekh, the markets would see this as a positive move,â said SujanÂ Hajra, chief economist and executive director of institutional equity at AnandRathi Financial Services in Mumbai.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBut given the kind of majority the B.J.P. has got, and the kind of control Mr. Narendra Modi would like to exercise on the Finance Ministry, it is more likely that a politician will be chosen for this post,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Hajra added that given Mr. Modiâs business-friendly reputation, he is expected to work closely with the Finance Ministry in deciding the course of Indiaâs economy, so the markets are unlikely to react negatively to his choice of a finance minister unless it is a complete surprise.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The announcement of the new governmentâs first budget, its economic road map, is the next big inflection point for the market and is expected by July.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âJudging from the anticipation in the markets since the exit poll results, for the budget the expectations will run sky high,â said Dilip Bhat, joint managing director of Prabhudas Lilladher, a Mumbai-based brokerage. âThere are some immediate actions which the market is looking forward to, such as the announcement of pending road projects, that would create a multiplier effect in terms of jobs and incomes for workers across geographies.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He added that he expected that public sector undertakings would be given greater independence to chart their own course of action and that some measures would be announced to get stalled infrastructure projects off the ground.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Analysts expect the new governmentâs budget to differ from those of the Congress-led government in that it will focus on encouraging investment over consumption, by reining in subsidies and stepping up infrastructure and investment projects. Many expect the government to announce a revamping of the tax structure, something investors have been eagerly awaiting.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âMr. Modi needs to put in place a framework to stimulate demand in the economy, and simultaneously spur private investment,â said Rahul Arora, the chief executive for institutional equities atÂ NirmalÂ BangÂ Securities, a brokerage based in Mumbai. âThe markets are waiting for his views on a taxation overhaul, the implementation of the goods and services tax and a timeline on the Direct Taxes Code.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He predicted that the current rally in the Indian stock markets, which have jumped since Mr. Modi and his party won a solid majority in the lower house of Parliament, could be sustained until the budget is revealed, and that the budget could fuel an even longer rally if it meets investor expectations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One possible action that could lead to a correction or drop in the stock market is a change in leadership at the countryâs central bank. Raghuram Rajan, who was appointed governor of the Reserve Bank of India in September, has been credited with stabilizing the currency, stemming inflation and improving the countryâs fiscal deficit position.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">However, since he has taken over, he has raised the benchmark repo rate, the rate at which the central bank lends to banks, three times â by a total of 0.75 percentage point to reach 8 percent â to tackle inflation, a problem that has long dogged India.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Such moves have been criticized by members of the B.J.P., including Piyush Goyal, national treasurer for the party, whoÂ <a href="//m.economictimes.com/opinion/interviews/you-cannot-control-inflation-by-hoping-to-choke-demand-piyush-goyal/articleshow/msid-30190284,curpg-2.cms" target="_blank">said</a>, âIÂ think Governor Rajan is only aggravating the problems and making it worse by increasing interest rates.â He added that the B.J.P. would combat inflation by increasing investment and accelerating economic growth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There has beenÂ <a href="//www.ndtv.com/elections/article/election-2014/post-election-showdown-looms-for-rbi-governor-raghuram-rajan-504220" target="_blank">widespread speculation</a>Â about the possibility of Mr. Rajanâs dismissal by a B.J.P.-led government, though he hasÂ <a href="//www.ndtv.com/elections/article/election-2014/raghuram-rajan-rejects-reports-of-tension-with-narendra-modi-led-bjp-507066" target="_blank">denied any rift</a> with the party. Mr. Jaitley has criticized the use of interest rates to curtail inflation but has beenÂ <a href="//articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-04-07/news/48939605_1_retail-sector-rbi-governor-raghuram-rajan-arun-jaitley">quiet on the subject of Mr. Rajan&#8217;s dismissal</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf someone is doing a good job, he will certainly continue,â he <a href="//in.reuters.com/article/2014/04/03/india-election-rbi-raghuram-rajan-bjp-idINDEEA320JE20140403">said</a> in a television interview.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Because Mr. Rajan has been viewed favorably by both domestic and foreign investors, analysts said a change in leadership at the central bank would be counterproductive.Â Mr. Parekh of HDFC Bank <a href="//economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/replacing-rbi-governor-raghuram-rajan-may-lead-to-a-sovereign-rating-downgrade-hdfc-chairman-deepak-parekh/articleshow/34797954.cms">told</a> The Economic Times this month that replacing Mr. Rajan at the helm of the central bank could lead to a downgrade in Indiaâs sovereign credit rating.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe removal of Mr. Rajan would not be a positive signal to investors,â said Leif Lybecker Eskesen, chief economist for India and Southeast Asia at HSBC Global Research in Singapore. âOne of the things that the governor has achieved is to strengthen the credibility of the institution, tightening monetary policy. You need to create credibility in monetary policy and bring about macro stability to encourage investment in the economy.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Besides, he said, the low levels of investment in India should be attributed to structural problems, not high interest rates. âInflation remains too high, and I think the notion that interest rates should be cut to support investment growth is inherently flawed,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The post of Reserve Bank governor has traditionally been treated as independent by governments, and economists predicted that the government would not remove Mr. Rajan so early in his tenure.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI would find it very difficult for a new government to replace a popular and an effective governor especially so early at the job,â said Tushar Poddar, chief India economist for Goldman Sachs in Mumbai.</p>
